@page "/"

<PageTitle>DotNetAgenticRepairKit</PageTitle>

<section class="home-intro">
    <p class="eyebrow">Portfolio demo</p>
    <h1>DotNetAgenticRepairKit</h1>
    <p class="lead">
        A custom .NET agentic AI remediation skeleton that pairs a realistic Blazor support workflow with a safe repair pipeline.
    </p>

    <div class="home-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tickets">Open Tickets</a>
        <a class="btn btn-outline-secondary" href="agent-dashboard">View Agent Runs</a>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="feature-grid" aria-label="Project areas">
    <article class="feature-card">
        <h2>Support Ticket Triage Dashboard</h2>
        <p>
            The sample application domain models ticket severity, customer tier, SLA due dates, assignment, escalation, and status transitions.
        </p>
    </article>

    <article class="feature-card">
        <h2>Agent Dashboard</h2>
        <p>
            A read-only local dashboard displays run history, repair reports, diffs, validation results, and other generated agent artifacts.
        </p>
    </article>

    <article class="feature-card">
        <h2>Agentic AI Repair Workflow</h2>
        <p>
            The console agent detects build and test failures, generates deterministic context, records local history, and produces structured repair outputs.
        </p>
    </article>

    <article class="feature-card">
        <h2>OpenRouter Repair Planning</h2>
        <p>
            Failed runs can send a focused context packet to OpenRouter and save a validated JSON repair plan without exposing local secrets.
        </p>
    </article>

    <article class="feature-card">
        <h2>Human Approval Gate</h2>
        <p>
            Repair plans require explicit approval before source files can be changed, keeping the workflow inspectable and controlled.
        </p>
    </article>

    <article class="feature-card">
        <h2>Safe Patch Validation</h2>
        <p>
            Approved full-file replacements are path-validated, backed up, applied, rebuilt, retested, diffed, and reported.
        </p>
    </article>
</section>
